trying to make it happen.

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:07.110
You know, we were just
trying to find a way

00:06:07.110 --> 00:06:09.980
to make food and
sell it and pay rent

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:12.020
and all this kind of stuff.

00:06:12.020 --> 00:06:15.330
But we had these people
come in from Chicago,

00:06:15.330 --> 00:06:18.060
and, oh, we heard
about this food truck,

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:22.390
and it's like, very
authentic Thai experience.

00:06:22.390 --> 00:06:24.774
And so they came,
and they were like,

00:06:24.774 --> 00:06:26.940
you know, we were just out
of [INAUDIBLE] yesterday,

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:31.090
and honestly, this experience,
it's like you're in Thailand.

00:06:31.090 --> 00:06:33.515
Like, there was even a
rat that scurried by.

00:06:33.515 --> 00:06:34.140
SPEAKER: Oh no!

00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:37.990
BRAD GREENHILL: And like,
all this kind of stuff.

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:40.371
And I was like, yeah,
it's real, authentic!

00:06:40.371 --> 00:06:41.677
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:41.677 --> 00:06:43.260
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
That's our mascot.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:43.570
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:06:43.570 --> 00:06:44.070
Yeah.

00:06:44.070 --> 00:06:47.120
SPEAKER: Well, it was
interesting the first time

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:50.437
that I went to the old
restaurant, which was Katoi.

00:06:50.437 --> 00:06:51.270
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:54.720
SPEAKER: I would say the
building is very unassuming.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:57.440
And I don't mean that in
a negative way at all.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:59.459
But I actually thought
I was in the wrong place

00:06:59.459 --> 00:07:00.750
the first time I pulled up to--

00:07:00.750 --> 00:07:01.070
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
It's a common thing.

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:03.690
BRAD GREENHILL: That was
very much intentional.

00:07:03.690 --> 00:07:04.530
SPEAKER: OK.

00:07:04.530 --> 00:07:06.214
Tell us a little
bit more about that,

00:07:06.214 --> 00:07:07.630
because it is--
the location makes

00:07:07.630 --> 00:07:12.690
sense, the story about being at
Two James as a food truck that

00:07:12.690 --> 00:07:13.690
is not mobile.

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:16.950
But then looking
for space close by--

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:18.790
because you obviously
found a market that

00:07:18.790 --> 00:07:21.060
was really into your food--

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:22.530
to look directly
across the street,

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:27.210
it looks like a white cinder
block, no-window space,

00:07:27.210 --> 00:07:29.070
also very small, is
very interesting.

00:07:29.070 --> 00:07:30.600
So tell us about that.

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:33.570
BRAD GREENHILL: So
when we were running

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:38.430
the truck, our third
partner, Philip, we met.

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:42.000
He had just bought that
property across the street

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.760
and wanted to put
a restaurant in.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:49.620
And he had kind
of a lame concept.

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:51.480
And so we were like,
hey, let's just

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:56.370
do the food truck concept
in the restaurant.

00:07:56.370 --> 00:08:01.410
And sort of the big thing that
we both kind of wanted out

00:08:01.410 --> 00:08:06.480
of it was we wanted it to have
like a rabbit hole effect,

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:09.390
so that there's just
this white building,

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:11.460
and maybe there's a
sign, maybe there's not,

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:13.200
or there's a red
light out front.

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:15.580
Or it's just very unassuming.

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:18.540
But then when you walk
in, it's like you're

00:08:18.540 --> 00:08:22.860
into this whole new
universe, kind of.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:29.601
So that was kind of what
we wanted to do with that.

00:08:29.601 --> 00:08:33.570
And ultimately, we put a
little neon sign out front.

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:37.409
But we pretty much kept
the old building intact,

00:08:37.409 --> 00:08:41.820
up to the false door of the
old entrance and everything.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:46.560
But we never-- we were just kind
of like, we're in such a rush

00:08:46.560 --> 00:08:48.720
to get open, like,
we never landscaped

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:51.360
it, never finished anything.

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:54.750
There was just like,
dirt piles outside,

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:58.140
and for like three months, there
was a giant hole in the ground,

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:01.140
because they were
excavating something.

00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:03.270
And so it never got done.

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:06.060
And we started working
on the addition.

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:08.730
And then that's when
the fire happened.

00:09:08.730 --> 00:09:11.520
SPEAKER: It is exactly that,
because when you walk inside,

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:13.950
you're like, wait,
what just happened?

00:09:13.950 --> 00:09:17.760
I thought I was walking into
almost an abandoned building

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:18.970
for--

00:09:18.970 --> 00:09:19.650
not anymore.

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:22.530
I think in Takoi, you've
done a lot of transformation

00:09:22.530 --> 00:09:23.220
on the outside.

00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:26.320
But I love that you kept
the inside of Katoi,

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:28.430
of Takoi, because
it's so beautiful.

00:09:28.430 --> 00:09:30.540
I've heard people
compare it to being

00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:36.420
in South Beach or SoHo, or
some of the more vibrant cities

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:38.290
around the world,
than even in Detroit.

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:42.210
But what did you model
the inside after?

00:09:42.210 --> 00:09:45.480
BRAD GREENHILL: I think
a lot of the inside

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:48.030
was sort of, before we
opened the first time, was

00:09:48.030 --> 00:09:51.420
a little bit kind of improvved.

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:55.110
We had a sort of aesthetic
that was planned,

00:09:55.110 --> 00:09:57.580
which was the bar in the
front, the dining room.

00:09:57.580 --> 00:10:01.290
And so it was kind of
like layers of an onion,

00:10:01.290 --> 00:10:02.130
like bookends.

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:04.390
Like, you come in, and
there's one experience,

00:10:04.390 --> 00:10:05.890
and then there's
another experience,

00:10:05.890 --> 00:10:08.920
and then there's the
kitchen experience.

00:10:08.920 --> 00:10:11.530
And the polycarbonate
was always planned.

00:10:11.530 --> 00:10:15.880
But our architect,
he's amazing, but he

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:19.180
can be, for lack of a
better term, a little stiff.

00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:24.970
And he wanted a specific
warm light behind the panels.

00:10:24.970 --> 00:10:28.410
And so when we're
building it, Philip,

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:32.470
who is our other partner,
he is a little bit more

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:34.130
irreverent and excited.

00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:37.110
And he was like, no,
let's have colored lights.

00:10:37.110 --> 00:10:41.620
And so like when Ish was
around, we kind of like

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:44.970
took all his work and like,
oh, no, let's do this.

00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:49.450
And all the stuff that he would
never allow, we kind of did.

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:51.700
And it took on its own
personality, everything

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:55.990
from like, there was a crown
of lights around the building,

00:10:55.990 --> 00:10:57.760
and stuff like that.

00:10:57.760 --> 00:10:58.900
SPEAKER: It's so inspiring.

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:03.010
And maybe someday when people
are in another city in the US,

00:11:03.010 --> 00:11:05.230
they'll say, oh, this is
just like being in Detroit,

00:11:05.230 --> 00:11:06.605
because you've
given us something

00:11:06.605 --> 00:11:08.375
really cool to go off of.

00:11:08.375 --> 00:11:11.410
BRAD GREENHILL: Well,
we wanted a restaurant

00:11:11.410 --> 00:11:13.727
that you could only
have in Detroit.

00:11:13.727 --> 00:11:14.560
SPEAKER: In Detroit.

00:11:14.560 --> 00:11:14.850
Yeah.

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:15.641
It feels like that.

00:11:15.641 --> 00:11:20.700
BRAD GREENHILL: And so keeping
the inside, no painting

00:11:20.700 --> 00:11:23.530
on the cinder block,
and keeping it all old,

00:11:23.530 --> 00:11:26.140
and keeping the graffiti in
there and stuff like that,

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:27.460
was all very parts of it.

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:29.460
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: It's
also really interesting

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:31.929
to note the fact that even
for Ish, our architect,

00:11:31.929 --> 00:11:33.970
this was the first restaurant
he'd ever designed.

00:11:33.970 --> 00:11:34.290
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:11:34.290 --> 00:11:35.860
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: So
you have four people--

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:38.650
I mean, three partners who've
never had a restaurant before,

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:41.440
brick and mortar, and this
is what they come up with.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:43.240
And another interesting
thing to note

00:11:43.240 --> 00:11:45.370
about the interior
of the restaurant

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:48.400
is that the booths
and the tables

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:49.870
are all extremely low-set.

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:50.310
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:50.800
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
What did you say?

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:52.180
It was Japanese inspired?

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:53.055
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:11:53.055 --> 00:11:56.860
And that was very much
intentional by the architect.

00:11:56.860 --> 00:12:00.870
He wanted everything to
be on the same plane,

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:06.700
and low-set, which is sort of
an Eastern philosophy of eating,

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:07.940
being close to the ground.

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:09.790
You know, a lot of
Eastern cultures,

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:13.300
people sit on the ground
or at very low tables.

00:12:13.300 --> 00:12:16.330
And so that was all
very intentional.

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:21.385
Ish, he thinks about things
that I would never think about.

00:12:21.385 --> 00:12:23.010
SPEAKER: That's a
good partner to have.

00:12:23.010 --> 00:12:23.956
BRAD GREENHILL: Great.

00:12:23.956 --> 00:12:26.266
SPEAKER: Well, Christina,
I want to give you a chance

00:12:26.266 --> 00:12:28.390
to tell us a little bit
about your background, too,

00:12:28.390 --> 00:12:30.120
and how you came
into the restaurant.

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:31.120
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Ooh.

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:33.190
Well, I'm originally
from Chicago.

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:35.470
I went to school in New York.

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:40.180
And after school, I thought I
wanted to do market research.

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:43.120
I was a business analyst
for the first two years.

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:46.270
And then it wasn't
really fitting me.

00:12:46.270 --> 00:12:48.310
And then I wanted to
go back into education.

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:50.530
That's kind of what
I studied originally.

00:12:50.530 --> 00:12:54.490
Went to Spain, lived
abroad, taught there.

00:12:54.490 --> 00:12:58.690
Still, something wasn't
exactly pulling at my heart.

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:02.390
I found my way in Philadelphia,
in part for a boy,

00:13:02.390 --> 00:13:04.112
in part for a job.

00:13:04.112 --> 00:13:05.800
I will confess that.

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:09.790
And that's actually where
I got my start in food.

00:13:09.790 --> 00:13:11.920
And so I just needed to
hit the reset button.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:16.370
I needed to do something where
I would find immediate results.

00:13:16.370 --> 00:13:20.170
I missed having a job that
had some physicality to it,

00:13:20.170 --> 00:13:21.860
some instant results.

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:25.840
And so I got my start
in a really tiny cafe.

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:27.950
And then pretty much
from there on out,

00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:31.300
for the past eight and
a half, nine years,

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:32.440
only worked for startups.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:34.640
I've only worked for
small businesses.

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:39.040
So from that, I loved being
able to wear many hats

00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:41.230
and just try on so
many different roles.

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:43.480
I mean, in many
ways, I was manager.

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:45.700
But I would also
be doing payroll,

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:47.920
or I would also be
doing the marketing,

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:49.690
or I'd be doing
the social media.

00:13:49.690 --> 00:13:51.850
So I think, similar
to Brad, I really

00:13:51.850 --> 00:13:55.150
enjoyed having that
entrepreneurial spirit

00:13:55.150 --> 00:13:59.650
and being able to work with food
and work within a community.

00:13:59.650 --> 00:14:03.140
And in Philadelphia,
people are great.

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:04.270
Philly's a great town.

00:14:04.270 --> 00:14:08.740
And I think I came in when
they were having their food

00:14:08.740 --> 00:14:09.550
renaissance.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:12.390
And that really kept me
inspired and kept me interested.

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:15.010
And so the last
place I worked at,

00:14:15.010 --> 00:14:19.450
I was running three different
locations-- one in New York,

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:22.770
one in a Whole Foods, and our
brick and mortar location,

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:25.480
which we're a hummus place.

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:29.740
And then next door to me,
actually shared a kitchen

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.880
with another restaurant that was
part of our restaurant group.

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:39.850
And I met Drew Pompa, who is the
original bar director of Takoi.

00:14:39.850 --> 00:14:43.690
He had known Brad and Courtney
and Philip for quite some time.

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:47.050
And he was telling me back in,
it was only May, he was saying,

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:48.790
I'm thinking about going back.

00:14:48.790 --> 00:14:50.950
I'm like, but you've only
been here for six months.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:54.520
Like, you haven't even seen
what Philliy has to offer.

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:56.170
And he started telling
me more and more

00:14:56.170 --> 00:14:58.690
about what his job was,
what his position was.

00:14:58.690 --> 00:15:03.730
Ironically, his restaurant had
thrown a fundraiser for Katoi

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:05.320
when it burned down.

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:08.200
So that was only
the first instance

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:09.709
that I had heard
of the restaurant.

00:15:09.709 --> 00:15:11.500
And so everyone in the
restaurant community

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:14.110
in Philadelphia got
together and raised a couple

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:16.540
thousand dollars for a
restaurant that none of us

00:15:16.540 --> 00:15:17.714
had ever been to.

00:15:17.714 --> 00:15:20.380
So there's a lot of camaraderie,
a lot of interest in this place

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:21.405
already.

00:15:21.405 --> 00:15:24.030
He was telling me that they were
looking for a general manager.

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:26.020
And I said, I'm pretty
happy with my job.

00:15:26.020 --> 00:15:30.700
And then he managed to convince
Philip and Brad to fly out

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:31.720
to meet me.

00:15:31.720 --> 00:15:33.370
And I thought that
was so incredible.

00:15:33.370 --> 00:15:34.630
That's so impressive.

00:15:34.630 --> 00:15:38.210
You know, only very serious
people, or crazy people,

00:15:38.210 --> 00:15:39.850
will do that.

00:15:39.850 --> 00:15:42.360
So we had a wonderful
conversation.

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:44.590
And I was a little intrigued.

00:15:44.590 --> 00:15:47.692
And I didn't feel like I could
make a decision from there.

00:15:47.692 --> 00:15:49.900
Within two weeks' time, I
booked a flight to Detroit.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:51.730
It was a 24-hour trip.

00:15:51.730 --> 00:15:53.920
I met Courtney,
the third partner.

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:56.230
And she whisked me around town.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:58.510
And she was like,
the velvet glove

00:15:58.510 --> 00:16:02.050
that made the decision
so much easier.

00:16:02.050 --> 00:16:05.400
She introduced me to so
many different people.

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:09.880
And I began to see what
Drew had been talking about,

00:16:09.880 --> 00:16:12.700
what all this intrigue
and all this excitement

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:15.370
and opportunity in Detroit
was, through Courtney's eyes,

00:16:15.370 --> 00:16:17.380
and obviously through
the rest of the team.

00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:20.950
So within a week,
I made my decision

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:24.472
to move and completely
try something new.

00:16:24.472 --> 00:16:26.180
And that's how I ended
up at this family.

00:16:26.180 --> 00:16:27.070
BRAD GREENHILL:
Yeah, little known--

00:16:27.070 --> 00:16:29.440
she doesn't even know
this fact right now, but--

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:31.540
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Oh no.

00:16:31.540 --> 00:16:34.960
BRAD GREENHILL: When we first--

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:38.770
Philip sent me out to
Philly to go talk to Drew,

00:16:38.770 --> 00:16:44.419
to gauge his interest in
coming back to Detroit.

00:16:44.419 --> 00:16:45.460
SPEAKER: To win him back.

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:47.850
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah, to win
him back, bring him back.

00:16:47.850 --> 00:16:51.190
And this was when
we were rebuilding.

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:54.280
And I met Christina
on that trip.

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:56.500
And I said to my
girlfriend at the time,

00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:58.420
I think I'm going
to try and bring

00:16:58.420 --> 00:16:59.887
her back to be general manager.

00:16:59.887 --> 00:17:00.970
She didn't even know that.

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:02.761
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
Oh, I didn't know that.

00:17:02.761 --> 00:17:05.175
BRAD GREENHILL: The seed
was planted early on.

00:17:05.175 --> 00:17:06.140
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
All the meanwhile, I

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:07.790
was feeding you food,
and making it nice.

00:17:07.790 --> 00:17:10.180
SPEAKER: Yeah, that's a lot
of wooing of you, Christina.

00:17:10.180 --> 00:17:10.510
BRAD GREENHILL: I know.

00:17:10.510 --> 00:17:11.530
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Yeah.

00:17:11.530 --> 00:17:13.339
BRAD GREENHILL: The plotting
didn't come till after we left.

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:13.619
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: OK.

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:14.380
BRAD GREENHILL: But
I was like, huh.

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:15.659
I had this idea.

00:17:15.659 --> 00:17:16.865
It was like, in my head.

00:17:16.865 --> 00:17:19.240
And then Drew was like, you
know, I think I have someone.

00:17:19.240 --> 00:17:20.800
And I was like, oh,
is it Christina?

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:22.460
And he was like, oh, yeah.

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:24.700
And I was like, yeah, all right.

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:28.000
SPEAKER: Well, we're not here
to promote any other restaurants

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.710
in Detroit, but I'm so curious.

00:17:29.710 --> 00:17:31.930
What was that
moment that you had?

00:17:31.930 --> 00:17:34.450
Was it a bunch of
other places that you

00:17:34.450 --> 00:17:37.600
went and saw that there was a
really vibrant food scene here?

00:17:37.600 --> 00:17:39.670
Or was there an
actual moment that you

00:17:39.670 --> 00:17:42.526
thought you could make
Detroit your culinary home?

00:17:42.526 --> 00:17:44.900
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Yeah, you
know, I think a lot of it--

00:17:44.900 --> 00:17:47.694
I had been to Detroit a
couple of times before,

00:17:47.694 --> 00:17:48.860
had some really great meals.

00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:51.220
I have a few friends
that are from the city.

00:17:51.220 --> 00:17:55.450
But I think it was more
about the opportunity

00:17:55.450 --> 00:17:59.340
to work with Brad, the
opportunity to work with Philip

00:17:59.340 --> 00:18:03.010
and Courtney, and
just the way that they

00:18:03.010 --> 00:18:04.780
felt about this
business and everything

00:18:04.780 --> 00:18:06.330
that they thought
that it could be.

00:18:06.330 --> 00:18:09.340
I'm someone that has
always chosen opportunities

00:18:09.340 --> 00:18:11.810
based on the people
that I get to work with.

00:18:11.810 --> 00:18:13.810
If I get to have a
really good team,

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:16.490
Lord knows how far you can go.

00:18:16.490 --> 00:18:19.450
So I mean, I don't know if
it was Brad's anecdotes,

00:18:19.450 --> 00:18:21.154
or if it was
Philip's unbounded--

00:18:21.154 --> 00:18:22.695
BRAD GREENHILL: Now
she's like, super

00:18:22.695 --> 00:18:23.880
annoyed with me all the time.

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:24.921
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Yeah.

00:18:24.921 --> 00:18:25.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:27.030
I feel like we're
on Sally Jesse's--

00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:29.620
SPEAKER: That happens
in good teams, though.

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:31.990
That's a really important
thing here for us at Google,

00:18:31.990 --> 00:18:35.230
too, is you spend most of
your life, actually, working.

00:18:35.230 --> 00:18:36.370
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Right.

00:18:36.370 --> 00:18:38.078
SPEAKER: Working with
the people that you

00:18:38.078 --> 00:18:41.420
work with is a really major
part of successful teams.

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:43.330
So it's exciting to hear.

00:18:43.330 --> 00:18:45.460
I want to talk about the
food for a minute, too.

00:18:45.460 --> 00:18:47.480
So I don't know
if you know this,

00:18:47.480 --> 00:18:50.140
but I was at the restaurant
on Saturday night.

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:52.780
And I thought it was
really interesting,

00:18:52.780 --> 00:18:55.510
because I knew I was
going to get a great meal.

00:18:55.510 --> 00:18:57.980
But it's very much
an experience.

00:18:57.980 --> 00:19:00.050
I hope that that's a
favorable adjective--

00:19:00.050 --> 00:19:01.091
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: 100%.

00:19:01.091 --> 00:19:02.390
SPEAKER: --that you use.

00:19:02.390 --> 00:19:05.920
When our server
came to our table,

00:19:05.920 --> 00:19:08.380
she actually said, I'll be
your guide for the night.

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:13.030
And all four of us at the table,
one a lot more culinary-wise

00:19:13.030 --> 00:19:16.960
than the three of us, we
noticed that right away.

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:19.060
And we asked her about
it when she came back.

00:19:19.060 --> 00:19:21.190
And she said, one
thing about Takoi

00:19:21.190 --> 00:19:24.555
is that we hope to awaken
all five of the senses.

00:19:24.555 --> 00:19:25.930
So we don't want
you to just have

00:19:25.930 --> 00:19:27.320
a sweet and savory experience.

00:19:27.320 --> 00:19:28.990
We want it to be everything.

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:32.230
Can you talk to us a little bit
about that, that notion that we

00:19:32.230 --> 00:19:34.270
have servers who
are more so guides

00:19:34.270 --> 00:19:38.279
that take us through
our experience at Takoi?

00:19:38.279 --> 00:19:39.820
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:19:39.820 --> 00:19:42.670
I think, just in
terms of nomenclature,

00:19:42.670 --> 00:19:46.840
I mean, the idea of server
and waiter is very antiquated.

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:51.940
And I think for us, we want to
have a level of inclusivity.

00:19:51.940 --> 00:19:53.620
We want people to
feel seen and heard,

00:19:53.620 --> 00:19:55.030
and this is a safe place.

00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:57.430
So the idea of having
someone be a guide

00:19:57.430 --> 00:19:59.710
is a lot more accurate
of what the experience

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:03.340
is for anyone new or a
veteran that's coming in.

00:20:03.340 --> 00:20:05.820
And so many of the
foods and ingredients

00:20:05.820 --> 00:20:08.500
are incredibly
unfamiliar to people.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:11.640
So the idea of a person
who is super knowledgeable,

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:14.550
who is super passionate, is able
to walk you through and help

00:20:14.550 --> 00:20:16.950
you curate the
choices of what you're

00:20:16.950 --> 00:20:18.600
going to be experiencing--

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:20.490
I mean so much of
what Brad's cooking is

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:25.620
is bold, flavorful, loud,
spicy, things on the extreme.

00:20:25.620 --> 00:20:27.930
So depending on what
it is that people need

00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:30.390
and what people want,
if you're a newbie who

00:20:30.390 --> 00:20:35.017
doesn't necessarily want to have
something that's super spicy,

00:20:35.017 --> 00:20:35.850
you know, certainly.

00:20:35.850 --> 00:20:38.465
Someone will be able to
provide something for you.

00:20:38.465 --> 00:20:40.590
There is something for
everyone on that menu, which

00:20:40.590 --> 00:20:42.360
is super exciting.

00:20:42.360 --> 00:20:45.090
SPEAKER: The connection back
to technology or social media

00:20:45.090 --> 00:20:47.730
or however you want to say it is
very interesting, because when

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:50.910
you do look at your menu online,
there are a lot of things

00:20:50.910 --> 00:20:53.990
that, to the novice person,
you're not familiar with.

00:20:53.990 --> 00:20:56.490
I'm going to say it
wrong, but the branzino,

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:58.771
the full fish that comes out.

00:20:58.771 --> 00:21:01.270
One of our guests was like,
I've never heard of that before.

00:21:01.270 --> 00:21:04.500
So I went to YouTube and I
watched a 10-minute video

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:06.450
on how to eat a whole
fish, because there

00:21:06.450 --> 00:21:08.790
is an actual technique.

00:21:08.790 --> 00:21:10.800
So talk to us a
little bit about how

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:14.670
you guys are using technology,
social media, or what

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:19.470
channels you're finding success
growing the business with.

00:21:19.470 --> 00:21:24.130
BRAD GREENHILL: Well, I think
we use technology every day.

00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:29.600
And I think that we'll continue
to use it more and more.

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:33.480
Everything from our
reservation ticketing system,

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:37.510
it's called Tock,
so it's online.

00:21:37.510 --> 00:21:41.190
And rather than-- we
don't have reservations

00:21:41.190 --> 00:21:43.800
in the traditional
sense, but you

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:49.900
can buy a ticket to come to
the restaurant with a group,

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:52.620
and then-- so it's similar
to going to a concert

00:21:52.620 --> 00:21:53.790
or something like that.

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:55.980
So that's one example.

00:21:55.980 --> 00:21:58.840
And of course, there's
Instagram and Facebook

00:21:58.840 --> 00:22:02.830
and stuff like that.

00:22:02.830 --> 00:22:05.940
But everything from
spreadsheets to--

00:22:05.940 --> 00:22:09.120
I think we only have scratched
the surface on how much we

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:10.050
can use technology.

00:22:10.050 --> 00:22:10.710
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: Absolutely.

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:12.126
I think there's a
lot more that we

00:22:12.126 --> 00:22:14.970
can do to maximize,
especially once we

00:22:14.970 --> 00:22:16.400
start delving more into video.

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:18.510
Brad always says, he
never wants to tell people

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:19.570
how to eat their food.

00:22:19.570 --> 00:22:20.486
BRAD GREENHILL: Right.

00:22:20.486 --> 00:22:23.310
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: But I think,
you know, a lot of times people

00:22:23.310 --> 00:22:25.590
will reference-- how do people
make decisions on where they're

00:22:25.590 --> 00:22:26.715
going to eat for a weekend?

00:22:26.715 --> 00:22:27.900
They're going to go to Yelp.

00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:29.150
They're going to go to Google.

00:22:29.150 --> 00:22:30.510
And they're to go to Instagram.

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:32.100
And so with all
those things, people,

00:22:32.100 --> 00:22:34.590
we rely so heavily
on those visual cues

00:22:34.590 --> 00:22:36.400
and those visual choices.

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:39.690
And by bolstering
up those pieces,

00:22:39.690 --> 00:22:42.150
it allows for
people to understand

00:22:42.150 --> 00:22:43.530
what they can expect.

00:22:43.530 --> 00:22:46.110
I mean, for me, I didn't
have the opportunity

00:22:46.110 --> 00:22:48.905
to visit the restaurant
before I decided to move.

00:22:48.905 --> 00:22:52.600
I didn't have the opportunity
to even taste the food.

00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:55.030
So in many ways, I was
coming in as a consumer.

00:22:55.030 --> 00:22:57.240
I was coming in as like,
a brand new person.

00:22:57.240 --> 00:23:00.360
And so from what I had
gleaned, based on social media,

00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:02.370
based on everything
that I had read,

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:04.905
was a lot of
important information.

00:23:04.905 --> 00:23:06.840
And I think the more
that we translate

00:23:06.840 --> 00:23:09.290
our story and our narrative
that way, the more powerful

00:23:09.290 --> 00:23:09.870
it can be.

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:10.453
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:23:10.453 --> 00:23:15.180
We are in an environment where
sight, sound, and motion is now

00:23:15.180 --> 00:23:16.160
cost of entry.

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:18.150
So it's more than
the Instagram's

