00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:58.470
And so that's kind
of loosely the theme

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:01.530
going behind the
food, is the idea

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:06.450
of what are the foods
near us, around us,

00:36:06.450 --> 00:36:09.300
that we're sort of
attracted to, and what

00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:12.330
are the foods that are kind
of attracted to each other?

00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:16.380
So that's sort of the
basis of creatively

00:36:16.380 --> 00:36:19.420
how I'm approaching it.

00:36:19.420 --> 00:36:22.900
SPEAKER: What's your soft
launch date or target open date?

00:36:22.900 --> 00:36:23.760
Do you have one?

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:24.780
BRAD GREENHILL:
That I can't say.

00:36:24.780 --> 00:36:25.988
SPEAKER: Is that a tough one?

00:36:28.395 --> 00:36:30.020
BRAD GREENHILL:
Sometime in the summer.

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:30.910
SPEAKER: OK, great.

00:36:30.910 --> 00:36:31.170
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:36:31.170 --> 00:36:32.660
Probably on the later side.

00:36:32.660 --> 00:36:32.850
SPEAKER: Great.

00:36:32.850 --> 00:36:33.810
Well, that's exciting.

00:36:33.810 --> 00:36:35.485
BRAD GREENHILL: Don't
hold me to August.

00:36:35.485 --> 00:36:38.300
SPEAKER: We'll be
looking forward to that.

00:36:38.300 --> 00:36:41.330
I want to allow time if
there's any questions.

00:36:41.330 --> 00:36:44.405
It looks like we've got one
over here to start with.

00:36:44.405 --> 00:36:45.030
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:46.750
Thanks, guys, for coming in.

00:36:46.750 --> 00:36:48.660
We really appreciate it.

00:36:48.660 --> 00:36:51.120
Takoi is definitely my favorite
spot in all of Detroit,

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:51.680
hands down.

00:36:51.680 --> 00:36:54.000
So thank you.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.640
One comment, and two questions--
sorry to be that guy.

00:36:56.640 --> 00:36:58.170
The comment is I
think it's awesome

00:36:58.170 --> 00:37:01.050
that with this new
Magnet restaurant,

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:02.742
that you're not shying
away from having

00:37:02.742 --> 00:37:03.950
open fire in your restaurant.

00:37:03.950 --> 00:37:04.825
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:37:04.825 --> 00:37:07.350
AUDIENCE: It's almost
like an homage to Katoi.

00:37:07.350 --> 00:37:07.975
So I like that.

00:37:07.975 --> 00:37:09.391
BRAD GREENHILL:
Well, the irony is

00:37:09.391 --> 00:37:10.880
that we're going
to have open fire,

00:37:10.880 --> 00:37:14.430
and then the design
that Ish has come up

00:37:14.430 --> 00:37:16.800
with for the whole front
of the house is all wood.

00:37:16.800 --> 00:37:18.329
So you know--

00:37:18.329 --> 00:37:20.120
CHRISTINA PONSARAN:
We'll see what happens.

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:21.203
AUDIENCE: Fingers crossed.

00:37:21.203 --> 00:37:22.971
BRAD GREENHILL: Be very careful.

00:37:22.971 --> 00:37:23.970
AUDIENCE: Two questions.

00:37:23.970 --> 00:37:26.330
One's real-- well,
not simple, but I'm

00:37:26.330 --> 00:37:29.780
just curious why Thai
was the selected food

00:37:29.780 --> 00:37:32.890
choice for Katoi, now Takoi.

00:37:32.890 --> 00:37:37.140
And then two, if you could
maybe expand a little bit--

00:37:37.140 --> 00:37:39.030
I've heard the story
from Courtney--

00:37:39.030 --> 00:37:41.160
on the transition
period, what happened

00:37:41.160 --> 00:37:45.242
between the fire at Katoi
and the reopening of Takoi,

00:37:45.242 --> 00:37:46.950
in terms of keeping
all of your employees

00:37:46.950 --> 00:37:49.260
on and bouncing around to make
sure that there was always

00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:49.990
something to do.

00:37:49.990 --> 00:37:52.920
And I also like the
story about the rally

00:37:52.920 --> 00:37:55.080
of all of the restaurants,
not just around Detroit,

00:37:55.080 --> 00:37:58.980
but around a lot of the Midwest
and even to the East Coast,

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:01.560
that kind of showed support
to raise money for you guys

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:03.744
to keep you moving.

00:38:03.744 --> 00:38:07.350
BRAD GREENHILL: Well, I'll
start with the first question,

00:38:07.350 --> 00:38:10.480
why Thai.

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:13.770
There's really no
great answer to it.

00:38:13.770 --> 00:38:16.430
It was a philosophy
and style of food

00:38:16.430 --> 00:38:18.660
that I just found
myself, probably

00:38:18.660 --> 00:38:20.520
about eight to 10
years ago, migrating

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:23.280
towards without really knowing.

00:38:23.280 --> 00:38:29.970
The concepts of sweet and
sour, salty, savory, spicy, I

00:38:29.970 --> 00:38:33.570
started incorporating
heavily into sort

00:38:33.570 --> 00:38:36.180
of my Italian
Mediterranean cooking I

00:38:36.180 --> 00:38:37.830
was doing at the time.

00:38:37.830 --> 00:38:41.760
And around that time is when I
started exploring Asian markets

00:38:41.760 --> 00:38:44.730
and discovered fish
sauce and all this,

00:38:44.730 --> 00:38:46.250
and started really studying.

00:38:46.250 --> 00:38:49.400
And I'm always a curious
cook, so I probably

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:51.750
have 400 or 500 cookbooks.

00:38:51.750 --> 00:38:54.910
So like, I'm always trying
to learn the next thing.

00:38:54.910 --> 00:39:00.780
And this was just what
I sort of migrated to.

00:39:00.780 --> 00:39:06.060
And so when-- but I
had an issue always

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:10.410
being known as the Italian
guy, or the Mediterranean guy.

00:39:10.410 --> 00:39:15.420
And so I would be doing
these Thai dishes,

00:39:15.420 --> 00:39:20.262
but labeling it on my menu
as like, Italian food,

00:39:20.262 --> 00:39:25.770
kind of renaming it based on
the ingredients that were in it.

00:39:25.770 --> 00:39:29.460
And so finally, when Courtney
decided do the food truck

00:39:29.460 --> 00:39:31.050
and asked me about
it, I was like,

00:39:31.050 --> 00:39:32.460
if we're doing a
food truck, this

00:39:32.460 --> 00:39:35.190
is when I'm just
going to switch over

00:39:35.190 --> 00:39:40.650
and just come at food completely
from a Thai, Southeast

00:39:40.650 --> 00:39:45.480
Asian perspective, rather than
sprinkling that into the food

00:39:45.480 --> 00:39:47.380
that I currently made.

00:39:47.380 --> 00:39:49.710
And the nature of
the food truck,

00:39:49.710 --> 00:39:51.890
being street food
and stuff like that,

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:59.390
felt like the natural jump-off
point to doing Thai full-time.

00:39:59.390 --> 00:40:02.805
Now, with going into Magnet,
it's like how am I going to--

00:40:02.805 --> 00:40:05.190
I don't know that
I can fully go back

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:12.710
to doing a different style of
food, because I'm warped from--

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:14.926
once you go Thai,
you don't go back.

00:40:14.926 --> 00:40:17.406
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:24.750
And but it'll be a
lot of fun revisiting

00:40:24.750 --> 00:40:27.120
sort of some food
I cooked before,

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:31.020
with new knowledge
and a new palate,

00:40:31.020 --> 00:40:36.480
and bringing sort of some of
that dynamic boldness of Thai

00:40:36.480 --> 00:40:41.460
cuisine into something that
may be more Mediterranean

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:47.160
or Italian or Middle Eastern or
something like that, or Indian.

00:40:47.160 --> 00:40:50.210
It's always just trying
to find new flavors

00:40:50.210 --> 00:40:55.290
and expanding my
knowledge as well as

00:40:55.290 --> 00:40:56.595
what we're feeding guests.

00:40:59.400 --> 00:41:00.510
Yeah.

00:41:00.510 --> 00:41:03.535
And then second question--

00:41:03.535 --> 00:41:04.160
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:41:04.160 --> 00:41:06.367
The second question
was the process

00:41:06.367 --> 00:41:07.950
that happened between
Katoi and Takoi.

00:41:07.950 --> 00:41:08.825
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:41:08.825 --> 00:41:12.640
So a lot happened
in between that.

00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:14.940
So the fire happened.

00:41:14.940 --> 00:41:18.390
And I got back, and the
first thing you think

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:25.230
is like, I have 42 employees
who don't have income,

00:41:25.230 --> 00:41:27.480
don't have a job.

00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:29.250
What are we going to do?

00:41:29.250 --> 00:41:32.660
And luckily, the community,
being as awesome as it is,

00:41:32.660 --> 00:41:34.330
rallied.

00:41:34.330 --> 00:41:37.860
And there was fundraisers,
seemingly like every day,

00:41:37.860 --> 00:41:40.590
everywhere.

00:41:40.590 --> 00:41:45.150
And so we used
that money to give

00:41:45.150 --> 00:41:48.060
to all the employees
a little stipend

00:41:48.060 --> 00:41:52.770
until they could find
temporary new work,

00:41:52.770 --> 00:41:56.040
because we knew we
couldn't keep everyone on.

00:41:56.040 --> 00:41:59.910
So we basically kept
like, a management team

00:41:59.910 --> 00:42:03.090
and some few others,
like a core group

00:42:03.090 --> 00:42:07.480
that we employed throughout
the duration of the closure.

00:42:07.480 --> 00:42:11.680
So on my end, I started
doing what I did before

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:16.980
and organizing pop-ups all over
the place-- so Motor City Wine,

00:42:16.980 --> 00:42:21.990
and we did one at Mabel Gray,
Grey Ghost, Selden Standard.

00:42:21.990 --> 00:42:24.390
And it also just
happened to correspond

00:42:24.390 --> 00:42:28.260
with the opening of
a place called Frame

00:42:28.260 --> 00:42:34.590
in Hazel Park, which their
concept was having prolonged

00:42:34.590 --> 00:42:37.120
residences for guest chefs.

00:42:37.120 --> 00:42:39.075
And so they were
just about to open,

00:42:39.075 --> 00:42:40.200
so it worked out perfectly.

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:43.460
We were there for three months.

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:45.930
And we did dinners
three days a week--

00:42:45.930 --> 00:42:50.590
or yeah, two seatings
three days a week.

00:42:50.590 --> 00:42:54.850
And that kept my
team pretty nimble.

00:42:54.850 --> 00:42:57.545
We were working on
stuff that whole time.

00:42:57.545 --> 00:42:58.920
SPEAKER: I attended
one of those.

00:42:58.920 --> 00:43:01.230
And I thought it was
interesting, because we just

00:43:01.230 --> 00:43:04.380
assumed that with this
pop-up at Frame, that we were

00:43:04.380 --> 00:43:07.210
going to have a table for four.

00:43:07.210 --> 00:43:10.050
And it was a happy
surprise that when we went,

00:43:10.050 --> 00:43:11.790
it was family-style seating.

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:15.000
So we were seated at a
table with like 15 people.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.650
And we had a chance to get
to know a bunch of people

00:43:17.650 --> 00:43:19.500
and talk about
the food together.

00:43:19.500 --> 00:43:22.210
So I loved that concept
and what that was.

00:43:22.210 --> 00:43:23.210
BRAD GREENHILL: So yeah.

00:43:23.210 --> 00:43:26.700
It was very much after the fire,
I felt more like a FEMA officer

00:43:26.700 --> 00:43:28.470
than like a chef, you know?

00:43:28.470 --> 00:43:38.340
But the community was absolutely
amazing, just so supportive,

00:43:38.340 --> 00:43:44.040
everything from chef friends
hiring some of my kitchen

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:48.840
people, even though they knew
it was going to be temporary,

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:51.120
or hiring servers, or whatever.

00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:53.116
And so it was great.

00:43:53.116 --> 00:43:54.990
SPEAKER: I think that's
the magic of Detroit.

00:43:54.990 --> 00:43:56.400
You won't find
another city where

00:43:56.400 --> 00:43:59.410
people are willing to help each
other more in circumstances

00:43:59.410 --> 00:43:59.910
like that.

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:00.784
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:44:00.784 --> 00:44:05.490
And I think the fact that
there was this public sort

00:44:05.490 --> 00:44:11.760
of rallying around our staff
that it influences places

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:16.380
like Philly or Chicago
or something else.

00:44:16.380 --> 00:44:18.840
Other people see
that, and it's hard

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:21.050
not to get swept up in that.

00:44:21.050 --> 00:44:22.390
SPEAKER: Yeah, in the community.

00:44:22.390 --> 00:44:23.265
BRAD GREENHILL: Yeah.

00:44:23.265 --> 00:44:26.040
And I think people
can relate to it.

00:44:26.040 --> 00:44:28.200
You know, they go
to work every day

00:44:28.200 --> 00:44:34.674
and they're like, if my place
burned down, what would I do?

00:44:34.674 --> 00:44:36.840
CHRISTINA PONSARAN: That
was certainly the mentality

00:44:36.840 --> 00:44:40.620
that the former restaurant
group that I worked for had.

00:44:40.620 --> 00:44:43.980
I mean, we all were very
aware that they'd also just

00:44:43.980 --> 00:44:46.470
been nominated for
a James Beard Award.

00:44:46.470 --> 00:44:47.700
And then just, what?

00:44:47.700 --> 00:44:49.920
A week or two later,
a fire happened?

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:53.790
So the Philly community
had this whole idea

00:44:53.790 --> 00:44:57.930
of a brother-in-arms scenario,
and wanted to do anything,

00:44:57.930 --> 00:44:59.850
to do everything that
they could do to help.

00:44:59.850 --> 00:45:01.860
So yeah.

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:03.660
SPEAKER: Tell us,
last but not least,

00:45:03.660 --> 00:45:05.460
because I know we're
getting close on time,

00:45:05.460 --> 00:45:08.239
tell us about the dish that
you brought here today for us.

00:45:08.239 --> 00:45:09.780
BRAD GREENHILL: So
the dish I brought

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:13.700
today is called Som Tum Thai.

00:45:13.700 --> 00:45:16.150
It's a very common--

00:45:16.150 --> 00:45:20.400
we serve it at the restaurant,
and it's very prevalent

00:45:20.400 --> 00:45:22.550
all over the
country of Thailand.

00:45:22.550 --> 00:45:28.560
It's one of the few sort of
traditional dishes that we do.

00:45:28.560 --> 00:45:32.040
In Thailand, there's probably
infinite variations on it.

00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:37.300
Everyone has their own
sort of version of it,

00:45:37.300 --> 00:45:39.720
depending on what region
of the country you're in.

00:45:39.720 --> 00:45:47.440
But the basis of it is som
is sour, and tum is to pound.

00:45:47.440 --> 00:45:52.230
So the idea is it's a generally
sour sort of salad that's

00:45:52.230 --> 00:45:54.900
built in a mortar and pestle.

00:45:54.900 --> 00:45:58.370
So the defining
characteristics--

00:45:58.370 --> 00:46:01.620
sour and spicy, always.

00:46:01.620 --> 00:46:04.710
So it's green papaya
that's been pounded

00:46:04.710 --> 00:46:10.500
with a little bit of garlic,
Thai chilies, tomatoes,

00:46:10.500 --> 00:46:15.690
long beans, and fish sauce,
palm sugar, little lime juice.

00:46:15.690 --> 00:46:21.270
Normally in Thailand, you would
always find dried shrimp in it.

00:46:21.270 --> 00:46:25.050
I like the dried shrimp in
it, but as a crowd pleaser,

00:46:25.050 --> 00:46:28.160
we tend to take it out of there.

00:46:28.160 --> 00:46:29.080
SPEAKER: Excellent.

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:31.460
I saw a lot of bowls
being filled back there.

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:32.920
So thank you very much.

00:46:32.920 --> 00:46:35.650
And thank you so much
for coming in for today.

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:39.880
Let's get one more round
of applause for our guests

00:46:39.880 --> 00:46:40.480
from Takoi.

00:46:40.480 --> 00:46:41.080
Thank you.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:43.530
[APPLAUSE]

